rComments: In retrospect, I'm happy that I took this class since I need BCH2333. But this class was a mess, to say the least.

Class notes are fill-in-the-blanks, so attendance is mandatory. He emphasizes well what is important for the midterms and provides very useful online sheets that tell you which meds you should focus on for the midterms. There is no textbook since he also provides summarized notes for each chapter which he posts online. Very lenient with grading too

For ANP 1105 he was great and taught well. I also had him for ANP 1106 which was very different, students basically taught themselves, and he also got confused on the content sometimes. His slides are overloaded with information but exams are only based on the slides so it's not too bad. His exams are by far the easiest (as easy as ANP can be).
A+ for easiness. C+ for the way he teaches. Go to class as they are fill-in the blanks. Can be rude if you upset him. A bit odd but you'll get used to it
Great prof! Definitely recommend! Removes questions half the class gets wrong!
Definitely a solid choice. Easy exams and decent lectures. Fill in the blank slides so you have to go to class. Not an amazing prof but I also have nothing bad to say about him.

He's the best anatomy prof at uottawa. If you need to take ANP 1106/1105, take them with Dr Feiner. His exams are reasonable and non-stressful, and they don't include fill-in-the-blacks like Dr Carnegie/Dr Savorys' exams. He's hilarious, even when he's not trying to be. He really cares about his students, and he replies to e-mails fast. I love him

His slides are very disorganized and he gets confused about his own lectures and sometimes does not know what he is saying himself. His exams however, are extremely fair and if I were to choose to take a prof for anatomy it would be him, considering if you memorize his slides you can get an A+. Questions posted after class- same format as exam Qs.

His slides are very disorganized and hard to read. Good luck trying to decipher them! They are also fill in the blank so you must show up for class. I recommend just reading the textbook, it's a lot easier that way.

Frank is a very dry professor, his lectures are long and pretty useless since he just reads the slides, but you need to attend in order to get the blanks. Overall, his exams are pretty easy. All the questions on the exam are worded in a way where you can figure out the answer if you know one of the labels on the diagram.

Slides are often unorganized and hard to decipher due to a surplus of words and phrases without context, needing 2x the span of time (compared to Copeland) to summarize his notes. Even though his slides give me aneurisms, his exams are extremely fair and arguably easy to get a good mark in. He only tests off his slides which are all MC.

His lectures are dry , but he makes jokes during the lectures which makes it fun . His exams are straightforward, no tricks AT ALL! If you attend the class , and know whatever is on the slides you will end up with A. His slides are from the book , page by page . Very clear to understand. Dont hesitate to ask questions before or after the class :)
He doesn't make his own slides, and doesn't really understand what's written on them. His exams are straightforward and have diagrams. Gives out hints in class as to what to study for the exams.

Although his lectures are painfully slow, he is very clear about what to expect on his midterms. He also removes questions that class did very poorly on. Went from a low 80 to a 97 on the first midterm. If you study the slides properly, you will do fine.

I found myself falling asleep a lot in his class, it's very hard to pay attention because he just reads off the slides. All of the things you need to know for the exam are in the lecture notes, but they can be disorganized and hard to follow if you are not a visual learner.

Nice man. Lectures are fill in the blank so you must attend class. His lecture slides are quite confusing and all over the place so I found myself to be re-writing all my notes before the exam. His exams are a weird format however, relatively easy. He gives you sample questions and the entire exam is in that format so understand how they work.
He is a really good prof, always open to feedback on exams. The class is an easy A if you memorize his slides. The exams aren't cumulative which is nice (2 midterms and a final exam).

The course is super interesting but is ruined by the fact that theres a different professor for each lecture, making the exam extremely difficult. Feiner is an amazing prof but again you have him for only 3 lectures and the rest are ran but many different profs. Exams are way harder then necessary. Attendance is mandatory.

Class is straightforward, study from his slides and you will do well. use the text book for added support. His notes are fill in the blank so attend class but beware he will mix up the material a lot, and requires students to put him in the right track.

Dr. Feiner is one of the best profs Ive ever had! Hes very organized and intelligent and knows his stuff very well. His lectures are engaging and his midterms and exams are fair. Study hard and you will get a good grade !

Excellent professor! Clear, concise and essay to follow. Exams are fair. Physiology is a challenging course, but Dr. Feiner makes it interesting and enjoyable. He is one of the best professors I have had. Work hard and study and you'll do just fine.

all of his slides are fill in the blank and he doesn't post what goes in the blank spaces so you must go to class. He screws up how he sets up his mastering a&p due dates and percentage removal when handing it in late so be careful about that. also says for exams that you don't need to memorize diagrams but you do
Show up to class in order to fill in the blanks on his slides. The midterms and final exams are only based on the slides but the online assignments are solely based on the textbook.

I really enjoyed taking this course and Dr Feiner was a decent prof that taught the course. The course is definitely lecture heavy and I would advise you to attend all the lectures of the class to get a good grade. The midterms and exam are from his notes rather than the textbook which is a plus. It was an interesting course overall!

Dr. Feiner is an amazing guy. So helpful and funny. He makes you want to come to class. He's one of those profs who just has a way of speaking and you understand him on the spot. He had that effect on me. A&P assignments are long, but the answers are easy to find, and those are easy 90's. I def recommend. Wish he was more lenient with grades tho.
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', 'Lots of homework', 'Clear grading criteria']

rComments: His slides have gaps which gives an incentive to go to class. You can still survive without going to the lectures because it's all in the book. There's a lot to remember. I find him funny, but not everyone does. His exams are very fair, no surprises there. Don't forget the Mastering A&P assignments. He also replies to emails extremely fast.

He is the best prof ever! everything is off the slides and the slides are amazing for reviewing. All exams are extremely fair. He is entertaining and really cares! The fill in the blanks ensure you go to class but they go by quickly with him!!! Awesome guy, love the suspenders.

Exams based solely off of slides. They're blank, so you'll have to show up. Well, not really, because you can fill them yourself from the textbook. Overall boring, occasionally funny and an easy prof.

Great dude, makes a course like Pharm as interesting and entertaining as it can be. His lecture slides are "fill in the blank" which is annoying but it gets people to come to class. His exams have to be the fairest I've taken so far in University. He doesn't pull curve balls on the exams, it has all been covered in lectures. Didn't need a textbook.
Just go to class and listen to the lectures. Study only off those lectures (literally nothing else needed) and you'll get an A. Easily the best teaching any of the ANP courses... take his class!
Great guy, knows his stuff and keeps lectures interesting. Approachable, fair exams. Would take again.

His lectures are very boring and confusing, but you can learn the material yourself by reading his slides. They have everything he can test you on- so you don't need to worry about knowing random facts from the textbook. Also, go to the Health Sciences anatomy tutorials (you don't need to be in Health Sciences)- they are golden and got me my A+.
Really sweet guy, lectures are long cause they are all fill in the blank so you have to pay attention. IF you study you can do well but his exams are hard. They are mainly memorizing.

bless his wonderful heart, he's too good to us. take his class if you can, everything you need to know is on his slides, and only his slides. always answers questions and then posts them as announcements for everyone to see to clear things up.

A monotone professor BUT... he only focuses on the important anatomy & leaves out the useless junk, so kudos to him. His powerpoint slides are fill in the blank, but the slides are based off the textbook, so you don't have to show up to class. Midterms are non-cumulative & are directly off the slides. He BEGS us not to study from the textbook.

Feiner is one of my favourite profs. he's really funny, super chill and genuinely seems like a great person. only know know the content on his slides for the midterms, which are usually super clear if you've studied. gets rid of questions if the majority of the class didn't answer it correctly. Really fair! Thanks for a great semester Feiner :)

Great prof and course! His lectures can be dry but are mandatory. His midterms and exams are very straightforward (directly from his slides) but the textbook and online homework really help with preparation! Overall, he's a grey prof, very funny and really cares!

He's not the best lecturer but he's really funny, its just the material that's boring. He really does try to make your life easy and will cut out a lot of anatomy. His midterms are literally off of his slides, so study those and you'll do well!

I was in Dr Feiner's patho and pharm classes, he is a great professor. One of the best profs I encountered so far at Ottawa U. I love the fact that he takes the time to summarize the notes and then go even further and gives you slides. My advice, take the time to read through the notes before class and attend lectures and you are golden. Awesome!

Absolutely loved this class! He is super organized and I loved his fill in the blank method of delivering lectures as it keeps you awake in class. ALL exams are noncumulative and literally no tricks everything is directly off the slides. And he literally begs us not to read from the book lol. Such a nice man Class averages high! TAKE THIS CLASS:)
Great prof, extremely fair exams (with appropriate adjustments for overly difficult questions). Would definitely take again/another course with him.

All the content you need is on his lecture slides, but he blanks out every second word so you have to go to class. Hard to pay attention in lectures because you are scrambling to fill in his blanks. Exams were easy but many questions and diagrams very ambiguous.

Curves his midterms and final based on how the class performs on specific questions. Posts his slides beforehand, but he blocks a lot of the content to make you go to class. Midterms were difficult to get over 90% in, but final was easier and it was curved a lot.

I'll admit he's boring but that's the only bad thing you can say about Feiner. He's monotone but incredibly clear with his lectures. His slideshows are comprehensive and he ONLY tests on them so it's super easy to study and get an A. He doesn't like anatomy so he cuts out a lot of the memorization and focuses on physiology. Take his course!

Probably the easiest of the 4 (or however many) profs in terms of study material. He's very big picture - doesn't want for you to get caught up in all of the details and he tells you what portions of his lecture notes he doesn't want anyone to memorize.  Still LOTS of content but relatively OK. Good luck.

Pathophysiology was probably the hardest course I've ever taken. You must show up to the lectures and take detailed notes to understand it. There was no mandatory textbook, and the exams are based on the slides. The course had a midterm worth 55% and a final worth 45%.

Anatomy was a really straight forward class. 60 multiple choice midterms, all directly from the slides, which were all directly from the textbook. Go to class, fill the slides out, memorize them and you should get an A.

Not the best lecturer, but his exams are very fair. As long as you read and understand the material in the textbook you'll do fine. His lecture slides are copied straight from the textbook so you really don't have to go to class, however they are fill in the blank.

Dr. Feiner gave a 40-slide presentation for each lecture. If you couldn't make it, the slides were full of blanks but could be filled in directly from the text. All material straight out of the textbook, but going to lectures helped as Dr. Feiner was funny and very good at making sense of the material. Extremely fair midterms and exams!

There are some profs that are bad, but we have to live with it because they are experts in their field, just bad teachers.  Him, he is not a pharmacologist or a pharmacist, and he is a bad teacher.  I have no idea why he is teaching that class.  He does not know what is relevant to teach so we have to read everything.
Great Professor! very helpful and down to earth. He is very consistent and clear in his teaching. Would definitely recommend him to anyone.
